  {
    "client_msg_id": "4CC852B2-632C-4E27-924E-10F9C66E8A15",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "Idealistic assumptions about computation (infinite memory, zero-time computations, etc) are at the crux of higher level programming. These simplifications are key to getting at the *essence* of a problem, not the *incidental* limitations of hardware or integrations techniques. However where many use this as an argument against higher level programming, I see the as *the central challenge eliminating incidental complexity*. There’s no silver bullet. There are a million little things we need to simplify with algorithms, hardware, protocols, etc. Imagine trying to eliminate incidental complexity on computers with only megabytes of memory. It’s basically impossible. The main way forward then was increasing memory. So that’s to say I empathize with Conal in just handwaving here, but also empathize with you in the same way that I would with someone who had to deal with computers with minimal memory",
    "user": "U5TCAFTD3",
    "ts": "1535846975.000100",
